<p><i><b>The Turn of the Screw</b></i> is a short novel or a <a href="/wiki/Novella" title="Novella">novella</a> written by American writer <a href="/wiki/Henry_James" title="Henry James">Henry James</a>. Originally published in <a href="/wiki/1898_in_literature" title="1898 in literature">1898</a>, it is ostensibly a <a href="/wiki/Ghost_story" title="Ghost story">ghost story</a> that has lent itself well to <a href="/wiki/Opera" title="Opera">operatic</a> and <a href="/wiki/Film" title="Film">film</a> adaptation. Due to its <a href="/wiki/Ambiguity" title="Ambiguity">ambiguous</a> content and <a href="/wiki/Narrative" title="Narrative">narrative</a> skill, <i>The Turn of the Screw</i> became a favorite text of <a href="/wiki/New_Criticism" title="New Criticism">New Criticism</a>.</p>
<p>The account has lent itself to dozens of different interpretations, often mutually exclusive, including those of a <a href="/wiki/Freudian" title="Freudian" class="mw-redirect">Freudian</a> nature. Many critics have tried to determine what exactly is the nature of evil within the story.</p>
